SIMPLE: perquisite
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Perquisite
<hw>Per"qui*site</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>perquisitum</ets>, fr. <ets>perquisitus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>perquirere</ets> to ask for diligently; <ets>per + quaerere</ets> to seek. See <er>Per-</er>, and <er>Quest</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something gained from a place or employment over and above the ordinary salary or fixed wages for services rendered; -- examples are, a fee allowed by law to an officer for a specific service; the use of a company automobile or other company property.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> perk.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pillage of a place taken by storm was regarded as the <qex>perquisite</qex> of the soldiers.</q> <rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The best <qex>perquisites</qex> of a place are the advantages it gaves a man of doing good.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Things gotten by a man's own industry, or purchased with his own money, as opposed to things which come to him by descent.</def>  <rj><au>Mozley & W.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perquisited</ent>⟦br⟧
